(42, 19, 46, 40, 23, 13, 13, 'My house is the house of prayer', 'Hypocrisy and Corruption in Worship', 'This connection highlights the theme of hypocrisy in religious practices. Both passages address the corruption of spiritual authority and the barriers it creates for genuine worship and access to the divine.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 46, 28, 12, 7, 7, 'den of thieves', 'Connection of Deceit and Oppression', 'This connection highlights the theme of exploitation in both passages. Luke 19:46 refers to the misuse of the temple as a ''den of thieves,'' while Hosea 12:7 describes a merchant who ''loveth to oppress,'' indicating a shared concern about deceitful practices.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 47, 41, 11, 18, 18, 'sought to destroy him', 'Opposition to Jesus'' Teaching', 'Both passages emphasize the opposition Jesus faced from the chief priests and scribes as they sought to destroy him due to fear of his influence over the people. This connection highlights a consistent theme of conflict between Jesus and religious authorities.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 47, 40, 26, 55, 55, NULL, 'Teaching in the Temple', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' daily teaching in the temple. In Luke, the chief priests and scribes sought to destroy him despite his teachings, while in Matthew, Jesus recalls his consistent presence teaching there before his arrest.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 47, 41, 11, 27, 33, 'chief priests and the scribes', 'Authority and Confrontation', 'Both passages emphasize the challenge Jesus faced from the chief priests and scribes regarding his authority. In Luke, they sought to destroy him, while in Mark, they directly question his authority in the temple.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 47, 42, 21, 37, 38, 'taught daily in the temple', 'Teaching in the Temple', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' daily teaching in the temple, highlighting his role as a central figure in the religious life of the people. The opposition from the chief priests and scribes in the first passage contrasts with the people''s eagerness to hear him in the second.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 47, 43, 7, 19, 19, 'sought to destroy him', 'Opposition to Jesus'' Teachings', 'Both passages emphasize the opposition Jesus faced from religious leaders. In Luke, the chief priests and scribes sought to destroy him, while in John, Jesus confronts their failure to keep the law, highlighting their intent to kill him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 47, 43, 8, 37, 40, NULL, 'Opposition to Jesus'' Teachings', 'Both passages emphasize the hostility of the religious leaders towards Jesus. In Luke, they sought to destroy him, while in John, they sought to kill him for his truth-telling, indicating a consistent theme of rejection by those in authority.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 47, 40, 21, 23, 23, 'taught daily in the temple', 'Authority and Teaching in the Temple', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus teaching in the temple, highlighting the conflict with religious leaders. The chief priests and scribes in Luke seek to destroy him, while in Matthew, they question his authority as he teaches.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 48, 16, 8, 3, 3, 'very attentive to hear him', 'Attentiveness of the People', 'Both passages emphasize the attentiveness of the people to the reading of scripture. In Luke, the people are described as ''very attentive to hear him,'' while in Nehemiah, their ears are ''attentive unto the book of the law.'' This connection highlights a shared theme of focus and engagement with God''s word.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 48, 40, 22, 15, 16, 'the people were very attentive to hear him', 'Attention and Opposition to Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the people''s attention to Jesus and the opposition he faced from religious leaders. In Luke, the crowd''s attentiveness contrasts with the Pharisees'' scheming in Matthew, highlighting the tension between Jesus and the authorities.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 48, 42, 20, 19, 20, 'the people were very attentive', 'Attentiveness of the People', 'Both passages emphasize the people''s attentiveness to Jesus, which influences the actions of the chief priests and scribes. The fear of the people leads them to seek ways to undermine Jesus, highlighting the tension between His popularity and their authority.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 48, 42, 22, 2, 4, 'the people were very attentive', 'Fear of the People', 'Both passages emphasize the people''s attention and influence on the actions of the religious leaders. In Luke 19:48, the people''s attentiveness to Jesus contrasts with the chief priests'' fear of them in Luke 22:2-4, illustrating the tension between Jesus'' popularity and the leaders'' desire to eliminate him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 48, 43, 7, 46, 49, 'the people were very attentive to hear him', 'Attention and Authority in Teaching', 'This connection highlights the people''s attentiveness to Jesus'' teaching in Luke, paralleling the officers'' recognition of His unique authority in John. Both passages emphasize the impact of Jesus'' words on those who hear Him, contrasting with the skepticism of the Pharisees.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 48, 44, 16, 14, 14, 'attentive to hear him', 'Attentiveness to God''s Message', 'Both passages emphasize the attentiveness of individuals to God''s message. In Luke, the people are very attentive to hear Jesus, while in Acts, Lydia''s heart is opened so she attends to Paul''s words.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 1, 40, 21, 23, 27, 'as he taught the people in the temple', 'Authority in the Temple', 'Both passages emphasize the confrontation between Jesus and the chief priests and elders in the temple. They highlight the challenge to Jesus'' authority while he is teaching, illustrating a direct interaction with religious leaders.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 1, 13, 24, 1, 31, 'taught the people in the temple', 'Priestly Authority and Service', 'This connection highlights the theme of priestly authority and service in both passages. In Luke 20:1, the chief priests and scribes confront Jesus in the temple, while 1 Chronicles 24:1-31 details the organization and duties of the priests, emphasizing their roles in the temple service.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
